SWINE FEVER, CLASSICAL - KOREA, SOUTH (02)
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Tue, 26 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.com>
Source: AsiaPulse via COMTEX, 26 Nov 2002 [edited]

Another hog cholera case confirmed in South Korea
--------------------------------------
Another hog cholera case was found in a farm here, near where the latest
animal epidemic case was reported on 2 Nov 2002, according to the National
Veterinary Research and Quarantine Service (NVRQS), Tue 25 Nov 2002.
The NVRQS confirmed the pig, suspected of being infected with [hog] cholera,
tested positive for the bacteria [sic, should be virus] after a serum test.
Incheon Metropolitan Administration said it has slaughtered 1200 pigs raised
on the farm and put another 2540 pigs within 3 kilometers under close
examination.
In total, 8 hog cholera cases have occurred in the country since the first
case of the contagious animal disease was reported on 8 Oct 2002 in Ganghwa.
In Ganghwa alone, 5 cholera cases have been found since early [October
2002], leading to a total of 7602 pigs being slaughtered.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
